Securing S3 Bucket :
--------------------
1. AWS SSE(server side encryption) S3-Encryption:
      how to enable >> go to S3 bucket >> properties >> Default Encryption & edit>> choose the option from encryption type
         Here‚Äôs what happens step-by-step when you use SSE-S3:
                     You upload an object to your S3 bucket.
                     Before S3 writes the object to disk, it automatically encrypts it using AES-256, a strong industry-standard encryption algorithm.
                     S3 manages the encryption keys internally ‚Äî securely rotating, storing, and controlling them.
                     When you download the object, S3 automatically decrypts it for authorized users
2. AWS S3 SSE-KMS: 
      üîê What Is SSE-KMS (Server-Side Encryption with AWS KMS Keys)?
      SSE-KMS encrypts your Amazon S3 data at rest, but instead of S3 managing the keys internally (as with SSE-S3), it uses AWS KMS (Key Management Service) to manage and protect the encryption keys.
      
      This means:
      Every object is encrypted with a unique data key.
      That data key itself is encrypted by a KMS Customer Master Key (CMK).
      You can control, audit, and rotate that CMK using KMS.
      
      ‚öôÔ∏è How It Works (Step by Step)
      
      You upload an object to your S3 bucket.
      S3 asks KMS for a data encryption key for your CMK.
      The object is encrypted using AES-256 with that data key.
      The data key is then encrypted (wrapped) by your CMK and stored alongside the object metadata.
      When you (or an authorized user) download the object:
      S3 calls KMS to decrypt the data key.
      The object is then decrypted automatically and returned.

       üß∞ How to Enable SSE-KMS
       1. Via the S3 Console
       Go to Bucket ‚Üí Properties ‚Üí Default Encryption.
       Choose AWS KMS key (SSE-KMS).
       Select an AWS-managed key or your own CMK.
      3. In Transit Encryption:
              Encryption in transit means that your data is protected while being transmitted ‚Äî from your device, application, or another AWS service to S3 (and back).
              Amazon S3 achieves this using SSL/TLS (HTTPS) ‚Äî the same technology that secures websites.
              So when you see a request like:
              https://my-bucket.s3.amazonaws.com/myfile.txt
              ‚Ä¶it‚Äôs transmitted securely using TLS encryption.
              üöÄ How It Works
              You (or your app) send data to S3 using HTTPS.
              TLS encrypts the connection, so anyone intercepting the traffic sees only scrambled data.
              Once the data reaches S3, server-side encryption (SSE) can then protect it at rest (if enabled).
              
              ‚Üí In-transit encryption = HTTPS
              ‚Üí At-rest encryption = SSE-S3 / SSE-KMS / SSE-C

      how to enable:     S3 Console ‚Üí Your Bucket ‚Üí Permissions ‚Üí Bucket Policy ‚Üí Edit
              "Condition": {
                "Bool": {
                  "aws:SecureTransport": "false"
                }
      4. Bucket Versioning :
              S3 ‚Üí your bucket ‚Üí Properties ‚Üí Bucket Versioning ‚Üí Edit ‚Üí Enable Versioning ‚Üí Save changes.
      5. Bucket Replication and Batch job:
                

